 *1272510244*Lunch in Singapore
 f:id:nishiohirokazu:20100429120237j:image
 
 It's like SimCity where long and narrow buildings are densely packed together. Building coverage ratio? Floor-area ratio? Are there any regulations on building-to-land ratio or floor-area ratio?
 
 <img src="http://gyazo.com/66667e04e89416e56ab82df71a531790.png">
 
 For some reason, when I searched by floor area ratio, I got Chinese search results.
 
 <hr>
 
 Went out for lunch, but forgot my iPhone so no pictures. Noodle + chicken dish for $3.8, or about 250 yen. Last night's dinner was at a convenience store, so it was expensive, but at the mall's food court it was about that much. At a restaurant outside the mall, it says "two meat and one vegetable $2.8", so I guess that means it costs about 200 yen.
 
 Stationery stores are horribly full of Japanese products. Kokuyo is everywhere. Convenience store drinks are full of Pokka. The 7-Eleven convenience store is full of them. And in the afternoon, they take a double-decker bus to Uniqlo to buy sandals and short pants.
 
 <hr>
 
 I heard that green tea is powdery like matcha, so I bought Pokka Oolong tea at the supermarket. 1.5 liters for $2.10. There is no 100 yen packaged tea like in Japanese convenience stores, but the unit price is not so different.
 
 It's super hot, so drinks are a must!
 
 *1272546593*Diary of Day 2 in Singapore
 I bought a Suica-like card, paid $15 and it says $5 is non-refundable card cost and $10 (700 yen) is initial add value. 700 yen seems like it would run out quickly with Suica, but I took 3 buses and 1 train and went to Merlion and Chinatown. I took a bus three times and a train once to visit Merlion and Chinatown, but I didn't spend $3. Transportation costs are cheap.
 
 Escalators are fast.
 
